After the acquisition of the high-resolution structural images, we perform high-speed functional recordings using reduced resolution 512 × 512 pixel images from 10 slices in steps of 40 μm along the z-axis, resulting in a brain-wide imaging rate of 20 Hz. Based on our depth of field (9.5 μm per slice) and the distance between planes, we cover a total scanning range of ~120 μm along the z-axis (i.e. the dorsal–ventral axis). In order to determine functional connectivity between brain areas, we begin by first identifying all voxels that show time-varying activity during the pre-stimulus state. For each voxel, we define the time-averaged signal as:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
